04645nam a22005775i 9780822390961DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223909617 a10.1515/97808223909612doi  a(DE-B1597)554734  a(OCoLC)1224277996  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.800967621 aMcIntosh, Janet, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Edge of Islam :bPower, Personhood, and Ethnoreligious Boundaries on the Kenya Coast /cJanet McIntosh. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (340 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection : 3300tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTE ON LANGUAGE -- tINTRODUCTION The Edge of Islam -- tCHAPTER 1 Origin Stories: The Rise of Ethnic Boundaries on the Coast -- tCHAPTER 2 Blood Money in Motion: Profit, Personhood, and the Jini Narratives -- tCHAPTER 3 Toxic Bodies and Intentional Minds: Hegemony and Ideology in Giriama Conversion Experiences -- tCHAPTER 4 Rethinking Syncretism: Religious Pluralism and Code Choice in a Context of Ethnoreligious Tension -- tCHAPTER 5 Divination and Madness: The Powers and Dangers of Arabic -- tEPILOGUE -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this theoretically rich exploration of ethnic and religious tensions, Janet McIntosh demonstrates how the relationship between two ethnic groups in the bustling Kenyan town of Malindi is reflected in and shaped by the different ways the two groups relate to Islam. While Swahili and Giriama peoples are historically interdependent, today Giriama find themselves literally and metaphorically on the margins, peering in at a Swahili life of greater social and economic privilege. Giriama are frustrated to find their ethnic identity disparaged and their versions of Islam sometimes rejected by Swahili.The Edge of Islam explores themes as wide-ranging as spirit possession, divination, healing rituals, madness, symbolic pollution, ideologies of money, linguistic code-switching, and syncretism and its alternatives. McIntosh shows how the differing versions of Islam practiced by Swahili and Giriama, and their differing understandings of personhood, have figured in the growing divisions between the two groups. Her ethnographic analysis helps to explain why Giriama view Islam, a supposedly universal religion, as belonging more deeply to certain ethnic groups than to others; why Giriama use Islam in their rituals despite the fact that so many do not consider the religion their own; and how Giriama appropriations of Islam subtly reinforce a distance between the religion and themselves. The Edge of Islam advances understanding of ethnic essentialism, religious plurality, spirit possession, local conceptions of personhood, and the many meanings of “Islam” across cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEthnic conflictzKenyazMalindixReligious aspects. 0aGiryama (African people)zKenyazMalindixReligion. 0aGiryama (African people)zKenyazMalindixSocial life and customs. 0aMuslimszKenyazMalindi. 0aSwahili-speaking peopleszKenyazMalindixSocial life and customs. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390961zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822390961423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822390961/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000